<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-518-700  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 518 700.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  August 8 1989* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Translation firm for IBM Japan. (International Translations andServices Company Ltd.)andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Yazawa, Naoyuki.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   IBM Japan Ltd. (growth)International Translations and Services Company Ltd. (management).andO;Topic:     Computer industryGrowthAgedEmployment OpportunityLanguage TranslationNew CompaniesJapanese Language.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>TRANSLATION FIRM FOR IBM JAPAN TOKYO, JAPAN, 1989 AUG 2 (NB) -- IBM Japan hasestablished a translation company, ITAS (International Translations AndServices Co., Ltd.) to be operated by its retired employees aged 55 andolder.andP;  The translation company will open for business on 18th September,backed six million yen or $42,850 of capital, which will be shared 35 percentby IBM Japan and 65 percent by the retired employees.andP;  The major business ofITAS will be translation of manuals and other technical documents intoJapanese with the English-Japanese translation system called Shalt, developedby IBM Japan to increase productivity.andP;  IBM Japan, like other Japanese firms,sets retirement age at between 55 and 60.andP;  The new company has set retirementat the age of 65.andP;  There are only 450 over-55-year-old employees among the23,000 employed by IBM Japan.andP;  But the ratio is expected to increase, andthis is one of several spin-off companies with which IBM hopes to stretch theproductive years of its loyal workers.andP;  (Naoyuki Yazawa/19890803)</TEXT></DOC>